[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] This example shows how elements can be assigned to slots in a shadow DOM based on their `slot` attribute (matched against the slot's `name` attribute).
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] First we define an `<article>` element that presents title, metadata, and article body information.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] The article contains a `<template>` element that will become a shadow root, because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] We don't need to set its `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute because named slot assignment is the default.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] The template defines elements that have named slots for "header" and "meta" information, and an unnamed slot for "body" information.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] The elements are styled differently so it is easy to differentiate them.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] Inside the same host, below the template, we have four elements for populating the slots.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] The `<span>` elements have `slot` attributes that match the `name` attributes on slots in the template, and will populate the corresponding slots.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] The two `<p>` elements are unnamed, so are both inserted into the unnamed `<slot>` in the "body" element.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] The example below should show the content of the slots displayed in the appropriate sections.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] This example shows how elements can be assigned to slots in a shadow DOM using manual slot assignment.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] With this approach, each element must manually be assigned to a particular slot.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] There is no default assignment, so any slot that is not assigned will be empty.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] This warning is later set to be displayed via JavaScript if the browser doesn't support the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] Next, we define an `<article>` element that presents title, metadata, and article body information.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] This contains a `<template>` element that will become a shadow root, because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute, and will use manual slot assignment because `shadowrootslotassignment="manual"` is set.
