[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] When a `DocumentFragment` value is passed, `Node.appendChild` and similar methods move only the *child nodes* of that value into the target node.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] Therefore, it is usually preferable to attach event handlers to the children of a `DocumentFragment`, rather than to the `DocumentFragment` itself.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] Since `firstClone` is a `DocumentFragment`, only its children are added to `container` when `appendChild` is called; the event handlers of `firstClone` are not copied.
[src:static-site-generation/elements-template] In contrast, because an event handler is added to the first *child node* of `secondClone`, the event handler is copied when `appendChild` is called, and clicking on it works as one would expect.
[src:static-site-generation/glossary-ssg] A **static site generator** (SSG) is a software used to generate *static* websites.
[src:static-site-generation/glossary-ssg] A static website is comprised of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files.
[src:static-site-generation/glossary-ssg] Most importantly static sites do not have server-side logic, so for any given URL, all users will receive the same content.
[src:static-site-generation/glossary-ssg] Authors write content in any form accepted by the generator, such as Markdown, reStructuredText, HTML, (and sometimes even React, and so on), and the generator compiles them into a set of optimized static files that can be rendered by the browser.
[src:static-site-generation/glossary-ssg] Static sites are commonly used for blogs, documentation, and other content-driven websites, which don't have data that needs to be fetched or generated server-side.
[src:static-site-generation/glossary-ssg] They are fast, secure, and easier to deploy, because they can be served from a CDN.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] The benefits of single-source publishing primarily relate to the editor rather than the user.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] The user benefits from the consistency that single-sourcing brings to terminology and information.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] This assumes the content manager has applied an organized conceptualization to the underlying content (A poor conceptualization can make single-source publishing less useful).
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Single-source publishing is sometimes used synonymously with **multi-channel publishing** though whether or not the two terms are synonymous is a matter of discussion.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] While there is a general definition of single-source publishing, there is no single official delineation between single-source publishing and multi-channel publishing, nor are there any official governing bodies to provide such a delineation.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Single-source publishing is most often understood as the creation of one source document in an authoring tool and converting that document into different file formats or human languages (or both) multiple times with minimal effort.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Multi-channel publishing can either be seen as synonymous with single-source publishing, or similar in that there is one source document but the process itself results in more than a mere reproduction of that source.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] The origins of single-source publishing lie, indirectly, with the release of Windows 3.0 in 1990.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] With the eclipsing of MS-DOS by graphical user interfaces, help files went from being unreadable text along the bottom of the screen to hypertext systems such as WinHelp.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] On-screen help interfaces allowed software companies to cease the printing of large, expensive help manuals with their products, reducing costs for both producer and consumer.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] This system raised opportunities as well, and many developers fundamentally changed the way they thought about publishing.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Writers of software documentation did not simply move from being writers of traditional bound books to writers of electronic publishing, but rather they became authors of central documents which could be reused multiple times across multiple formats.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] The first single-source publishing project was started in 1993 by Cornelia Hofmann at Schneider Electric in Seligenstadt, using software based on Interleaf to automatically create paper documentation in multiple languages based on a single original source file.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] XML, developed during the mid- to late-1990s, was also significant to the development of single-source publishing as a method.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] XML, a markup language, allows developers to separate their documentation into two layers: a shell-like layer based on presentation and a core-like layer based on the actual written content.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] This method allows developers to write the content only one time while switching it in and out of multiple different formats and delivery methods.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] The concept behind this usage was that complex, hierarchical content that did not lend itself to discrete componentization could be used across a variety of requirements by tagging the differences within a single document using the capabilities built into SGML and XML.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Ford, for example, was able to tag its single owner's manual files so that 12 model years could be generated via a resolution script running on the single completed file.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Pratt & Whitney, likewise, was able to tag up to 20 subsets of its jet engine manuals in single-source files, calling out the desired version at publication time.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] World Book Encyclopedia also used the concept to tag its articles for American and British versions of English.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Starting from the early 2000s, single-source publishing was used with an increasing frequency in the field of technical translation.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] It is still regarded as the most efficient method of publishing the same material in different languages.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Once a printed manual was translated, for example, the online help for the software program which the manual accompanies could be automatically generated using the method.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Metadata could be created for an entire manual and individual pages or files could then be translated from that metadata with only one step, removing the need to recreate information or even database structures.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Although single-source publishing is now decades old, its importance has increased urgently as of the 2010s.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] As consumption of information products rises and the number of target audiences expands, so does the work of developers and content creators.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Within the industry of software and its documentation, there is a perception that the choice is to embrace single-source publishing or render one's operations obsolete.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] Editors using single-source publishing have been criticized for below-standard work quality, leading some critics to describe single-source publishing as the "conveyor belt assembly" of content creation.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] While heavily used in technical translation, there are risks of error in regard to indexing.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] While two words might be synonyms in English, they may not be synonyms in another language.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] In a document produced via single-sourcing, the index will be translated automatically and the two words will be rendered as synonyms.
[src:static-site-generation/single-source-publishing] This is because they are synonyms in the source language, while in the target language they are not.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] SSGs typically consist of a template written in HTML with a templating system, such as Liquid (Jekyll) or Go template (Hugo).
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] The same structure (typically a Git repository) includes content in a plain-text format such as Markdown or reStructuredText, or in a structural meta format such as JSON or XML.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] A single plain-text file may correspond to a single web page.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] Alternatively, a single structural metadata file may correspond to an entire website if a single-page application framework like AngularJS is used.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] The website variable settings are stored in a plaintext configuration file `_config.yml` (YAML), `_config.toml` (TOML) or `_config.json` (JSON).
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] Page files typically also start with a YAML, TOML, or JSON preamble to define variables such as title, permalink, or date.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] Files with names that begin with an underscore (`_`) such as `_index.md` (as opposed to `index.md`) are considered templates or archetypes and are thus not rendered as pages themselves.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] Several hundred SSGs have been documented to exist, with the vast majority being written in languages that are already prominent on the web, such as Python, Go, JavaScript and TypeScript.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] Many *server-side template systems* have the option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existing software adapted for this task.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for web use, running on CGI.
[src:static-site-generation/static-site-generator] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, starting with SSI.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] A **static web page**, sometimes called a **flat page** or a **stationary page**, is a web page that is delivered to a web browser exactly as stored, in contrast to dynamic web pages which are generated by a web application.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] Consequently, a static web page displays the same information for all users, from all contexts, subject to modern capabilities of a web server to negotiate content-type or language of the document where such versions are available and the server is configured to do so.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] However, a webpage's JavaScript can introduce dynamic functionality which may make the static web page dynamic.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] Static web pages are often HTML documents, stored as files in the file system and made available by the web server over HTTP (nevertheless URLs ending with ".html" are not always static).
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] However, loose interpretations of the term could include web pages stored in a database, and could even include pages formatted using a template and served through an application server, as long as the page served is unchanging and presented essentially as stored.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] The content of static web pages remains stationary irrespective of the number of times it is viewed.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] Such web pages are suitable for the contents that rarely need to be updated, though modern web template systems are changing this.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] Maintaining large numbers of static pages as files can be impractical without automated tools, such as static site generators.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] Any personalization or interactivity has to run client-side, which is restricting.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] Cloud-based website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, offer no-code platforms for creating static and dynamic web pages through graphical interfaces, without requiring programming expertise.
[src:static-site-generation/static-web-page] Static site generators are applications that compile static websites - typically populating HTML templates in a predefined folder and file structure, with content supplied in a format such as Markdown or AsciiDoc.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] A **web template system** in web publishing allows web designers and developers to work with *web templates* to automatically generate custom web pages, such as the results from a search.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] This reuses static web page elements while defining dynamic elements based on web request parameters.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Web templates support static content, providing basic structure and appearance.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Developers can implement templates from content management systems, web application frameworks, and HTML editors.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] The template and content resources are processed and combined by the template engine to mass-produce web documents, each with a similar visual format.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, web documents include any of various output formats for transmission over the web via HTTP, HTTPS, or another Internet protocol.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] A template processor (also known as a template engine or template parser) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] The language that the templates are written in is known as a template language or templating language.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] With the model typically held in a relational database, the remaining components of the MVC architecture are the control and view.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] In the simplest of systems these two are not separated.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] However, adapting the separation of concerns principle one can completely decouple the relationships.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] A web browser and web server are a client–server architecture.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Sites often also use a web cache to improve performance.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] In many implementations, template files contain variables or placeholders that are replaced with data supplied by an application when the page is generated.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] The source code of the template engine can be proprietary or open source.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Many template systems are a component of a larger programming platform or framework.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] They are referred to as the "platform's template system".
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Some template systems have the option of substituting a different template language or engine.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Programming languages such as Perl, Ruby, C, and Java support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] JavaServer Pages (JSP), PHP, and Active Server Pages (ASP with VBScript, JScript or other languages) are examples, themselves, of web template engines.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] These technologies are typically used in server-side templating systems, but could be adapted for use on an "edge-side" proxy or for static page generation.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Static site generators are engines that use flat text input files like markdown and asciidoc to generate a static web page.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Examples of this include Jekyll (Liquid, Ruby), Hugo (Go templates), and Pelican (Jinja2, Python).
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Some hosted website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, provide template-based systems that allow users to create static and dynamic web pages through graphical user interfaces rather than traditional programming.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] HTML editors often use web template systems to produce only static web pages.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] These can be viewed as a ready-made web design, used to mass-produce "cookie-cutter" websites for rapid deployment.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] They also commonly include themes in place of CSS styles.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] In general, the template language is used only with the editor's software.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] FrontPage and Dreamweaver were once the most popular editors with template sub-systems.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] A Flash web template uses Macromedia Flash to create visually interactive sites.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Many *server-side template systems* have an option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existent software adapted for this task.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for the web use, running on CGI.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, started with SSI.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Technically, the methodology of embedding programming languages within HTML (or XML, etc.), used in many "server-side included script languages" are also templates.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] All of them are Embedded complex languages.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] There are also preprocessors used as server-side template engines.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] As for edge-side template and inclusion systems, "edge-side" refers to web servers that reside in the space between the client (browser) and the originating server.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] They are often referred to as "reverse-proxy" servers.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] These servers are generally tasked with reducing the load and traffic on originating servers by caching content such as images and page fragments, and delivering this to the browser in an efficient manner.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Basic Edge Side Includes (ESI) is an SSI-like language.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] ESI has been implemented for content delivery networks.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] The ESI template language may also be implemented in web browsers using JavaScript and Ajax, or via a browser "plug-in".
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] Many web browsers can apply an XSLT stylesheet to XML data that transforms the data into an XHTML document, thereby providing template functionality in the browser itself.
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] The most simple form is transclusions (HTML frames).
[src:static-site-generation/web-template-system] In other cases dynamic web pages are needed.
